{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17519632","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17519632"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:14:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:14:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13056"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13056","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13056"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.05,0.05,0.71,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5493"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85043"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5493","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5493"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13056"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69249"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"355"},{"type":"tags","id":"381"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1258"},{"type":"tags","id":"9339"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"28916"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31413"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85043","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/85043"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of early satiety, postprandial fullness, and occasional retrosternal discomfort after meals. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She works as an accountant and has never smoked. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination is unremarkable. A barium swallow is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Achalasia","Gastroparesis","Carcinoma of the gastric antrum","Para-oesophageal hernia","Epiphrenic diverticulum"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe barium swallow demonstrates herniation of the gastric fundus through the diaphragmatic hiatus while the gastro-oesophageal junction remains in its normal anatomical position. This is characteristic of a \u003Cstrong\u003Epara-oesophageal hernia\u003C/strong\u003E. The presence of a fluid level suggests partial obstruction, which explains the patient\u0027s symptoms of early satiety and postprandial fullness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAchalasia\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with dysphagia to both solids and liquids, regurgitation, and chest pain. The barium swallow would show a dilated oesophagus with a characteristic \u0027bird\u0027s beak\u0027 appearance at the lower oesophageal sphincter, which is not seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastroparesis\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by delayed gastric emptying without mechanical obstruction. While it can cause early satiety and postprandial fullness, the barium study would show retained gastric contents but normal anatomical positioning of the stomach.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarcinoma of the gastric antrum\u003C/strong\u003E would typically show an irregular filling defect or stricture on barium studies, not the herniation of gastric fundus seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpiphrenic diverticulum\u003C/strong\u003E appears as an outpouching from the distal oesophagus on barium studies, not the herniation of stomach seen in this image.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPara-oesophageal hernias are often asymptomatic and found incidentally. When symptomatic, they can present with early satiety, postprandial fullness, and chest discomfort. Surgical repair is indicated for symptomatic patients or those with complications such as obstruction or strangulation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Para-oesophageal hernias are characterised by herniation of the gastric fundus through the diaphragmatic hiatus while the gastro-oesophageal junction remains in normal position.","Most para-oesophageal hernias are asymptomatic and found incidentally on imaging.","Surgical repair is indicated for symptomatic para-oesophageal hernias or those with complications such as obstruction or strangulation."],"references":["Roman S, Kahrilas PJ. The diagnosis and management of hiatus hernia. BMJ 2014;349:g6154. Available at: https://www.bmj.com/content/349/bmj.g6154"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69249"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13056"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20151"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20151","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20151"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e25632a5-5827-4825-80c9-2c4e9cd872de.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e25632a5-5827-4825-80c9-2c4e9cd872de.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":382,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69249","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/69249"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-14T10:13:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-14T10:14:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5493"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85043"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","sy